title SLC reach tier — the budget used Pixel widens who can broadcast, audience stays web-reachable
prompt Keaton asked for the best budget/cheap/used/refurbished Android device to widen customer potential if we modify our first SLC -- write and ship.
think grounded the answer in dated (July 2026) research rather than guessing: the honest best budget sovereign-capable device is a used Google Pixel -- 7a (~$150-220 refurb, or ~$298 pre-flashed GrapheneOS) as the reach floor, 8a (~$250, security to 2031 on the 7-year policy) as the best value. Named the skips (carrier-financed locked bootloaders, Pixel 6a battery recall, Pixel 6/earlier end-of-support).
think reasoned why used Pixel is the reach sweet spot: cheap AND abundant (deep refurb market), one of the few cheap Androids with a genuinely unlockable bootloader (most budget carrier phones are locked), and the widest sovereign-ROM support of any family -- plus you can buy it pre-flashed with GrapheneOS, removing the flashing-skill barrier that would otherwise cap reach.
think held the honest tension the Glowphone study already named: the used Pixel is GrapheneOS-hardened yet runs the least firmware-free silicon, so the two device tiers are complementary not competing -- Fairphone leads on repair + firmware-freedom (own-it-fully, ~$600), used Pixel leads on hardened-security + low-cost + abundance (reach). Both de-Googled and sovereign; a person picks by which value they weigh most.
think named the SLC modification precisely without touching the green L1 core: broaden the broadcaster-client target from Fairphone-only to any de-Googled-capable cheap used Android (Pixel 7a/8a lead, ~4x cheaper entry), lower the skill barrier via pre-flashed devices, and keep the audience platform-agnostic over the open-web WebSocket bridge -- reach on both the broadcasting and watching sides, sovereignty uncompromised.
think this answer also encodes the prior turn's Android-over-iOS decision (a used sovereign de-Googled Android is only possible because Android allows it; iOS forbids the whole path), so the reach tier is consistent with the TAME-alignment reasoning without re-litigating it.
think "write and ship" is an explicit ship instruction, so this send does commit-push-merge to main.
